<section id="intro" class="chapter">
    <h2>1. Introduction: The Lifeblood of the Red Army</h2>
    <p>
        On the brutal Eastern Front, trucks were as vital as rifles. They brought ammunition to the front,  
        evacuated civilians, and kept entire armies from starvation. Soviet drivers worked through snowstorms,  
        artillery bombardments, and lethal supply gaps.
    </p>
    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/a/a5/ZIS-5V_Soviet_truck.jpg" alt="ZIS-5 Truck">
        <p><em>The ZIS-5: the backbone of Soviet wartime transport.</em></p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="vehicles" class="chapter">
    <h2>2. Vehicles of the Eastern Front</h2>

    <h3>ZIS-5</h3>
    <p>A rugged pre-war design with simple mechanics. Easy to repair with limited tools.</p>
    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c5/ZIS-5.jpg">
    </div>

    <h3>GAZ-AA</h3>
    <p>Light truck ideal for urban and rural courier missions.</p>

    <h3>Studebaker US6 (Lend-Lease)</h3>
    <p>Beloved by drivers for reliability, traction, and cabin comfort. Many Katyusha launchers were mounted on them.</p>
</section>

<section id="routes" class="chapter">
    <h2>3. Strategic Routes & Extreme Conditions</h2>

    <h3>Road of Life (Lake Ladoga)</h3>
    <p>Drivers crossed frozen lakes to reach besieged Leningrad, dodging shells and thin ice.</p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3e/Road_of_Life_Leningrad.jpg" alt="Road of Life">
    </div>

    <h3>Rasputitsa Mud Seasons</h3>
    <p>Spring and fall rains turned roads to bottomless mud. Many trucks were pulled by horses or other trucks.</p>

    <h3>Steppe Convoys</h3>
    <p>Long, windy roads across open plains exposed drivers to German aircraft attacks.</p>
</section>

<section id="safety" class="chapter">
    <h2>4. Safety & Frontline Protocols</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Lights Off:</strong> Headlights forbidden within 20 km of the front.</li>
        <li><strong>Camouflage Nets:</strong> Used at every stop to prevent air attack.</li>
        <li><strong>Convoy Gaps:</strong> Maintain 80–100 meters under threat of strafing.</li>
        <li><strong>Emergency Rations:</strong> Drivers must carry dried fish, rye bread, and sunflower seeds.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="maintenance" class="chapter">
    <h2>5. Field Repairs Under Fire</h2>

    <h3>Essential Tools</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>Hand crank</li>
        <li>Wooden blocks for jacking on mud</li>
        <li>Spare spark plugs</li>
        <li>Cloth insulation for frozen carburetors</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Common Fixes</h3>
    <p><strong>Broken leaf springs:</strong> Reinforce with scavenged steel wire.</p>
    <p><strong>Frozen fuel lines:</strong> Warm with cloth soaked in hot water.</p>
    <p><strong>Shot tires:</strong> Fill with hay or rope to limp to a depot.</p>
</section>

<section id="life" class="chapter">
    <h2>6. Life on the Road: Hardships & Heroism</h2>
    <p>Red Army drivers slept in cabs, dug snow shelters, and often fought as infantry when convoys were overrun.</p>

    <blockquote>
        “A truck can save a battalion. A brave driver can save a city.”
    </blockquote>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/0c/Lend-Lease_Studebaker_US6_in_Red_Army_service.jpg">
        <p><em>Lend-Lease Studebaker US6 delivering Katyusha rockets.</em></p>
    </div>
</section>

